"en":{"1380–":"1380–Deceased","1380–Female":"1380–Deceased","1375–Male":"1375–Deceased","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1355–Male":"1355–Deceased","1360–Female":"1360–Deceased","1400":"1400","1355":"1355","1375":"1375","1395":"1395","1450":"1450","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hamshar","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Hampshire  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hampshire","meanings":["English:","(Yorkshire): habitational name from the southern English county so called, which derives its name from <i>Hampton</i> (i.e. the port of Southampton) + Old English <i>scīr</i> ‘division, district’. The County was formerly called <i>Southamptonshire</i>.","(Surrey and Kent): habitational name from the area of Hallamshire in southern Yorkshire, named from   Hallam   + Middle English <i>schir</i> ‘division’, ‘administrative region’ (Old English <i>scīr</i>). The surname is most common in Yorkshire, where this second derivation is most likely to be the source."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Elizabeth Hamshar was born in 1380, in England, United Kingdom, her father, William Hamshar, was 25 and her mother, Elizabeth Webb, was 20. She married Thomas Ade in 1395, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1380–":"1380–Surnud","1380–Female":"1380–Surnud","1375–Male":"1375–Surnud","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1355–Male":"1355–Surnud","1360–Female":"1360–Surnud","1400":"1400","1355":"1355","1375":"1375","1395":"1395","1450":"1450","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","England":"England"},"fi":{"1380–":"1380–Kuollut","1380–Female":"1380–Kuollut","1375–Male":"1375–Kuollut","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1355–Male":"1355–Kuollut","1360–Female":"1360–Kuollut","1400":"1400","1355":"1355","1375":"1375","1395":"1395","1450":"1450","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","England":"England"},"fr":{"1380–":"1380–Décédée","1380–Female":"1380–Décédée","1375–Male":"1375–Décédé","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1355–Male":"1355–Décédé","1360–Female":"1360–Décédée","1400":"1400","1355":"1355","1375":"1375","1395":"1395","1450":"1450","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Elizabeth Hamshar est née en 1380, à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, William Hamshar, avait 25 ans et sa mère, Elizabeth Webb, avait 20 ans. Elle a épousé Thomas Ade en 1395, à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"1380–":"1380–Verstorben","1380–Female":"1380–Verstorben","1375–Male":"1375–Verstorben","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1355–Male":"1355–Verstorben","1360–Female":"1360–Verstorben","1400":"1400","1355":"1355","1375":"1375","1395":"1395","1450":"1450","1360":"1360","1380":"1380","England":"England